.gitignore

.gitignore is a special text file in a Git repository.
It tells Git which files or directories to ignore — meaning Git will not track, stage, or commit them.
Purpose: prevent sensitive files, temporary files, or unnecessary files from being added to the repo.
Think of .gitignore as a “do not track” list for Git.

Step 1: Initialize Git repository
git init

Step 2: Create some sample files
echo "This is my personal note" > note.txt
echo "SECRET_KEY=12345" > .env
mkdir temp
echo "Temporary file" > temp/temp.txt

Step 3: Create .gitignore
vi .gitignore
.env
temp/

Step 4: Check which files Git sees
git status

if we want to forec add the ignored file
git add -f per.txt
vi .gittgnore
remove &wq!
